library(tidyverse)

library(palmerpenguins)

library(janitor)

library(lubridate)

library(gt)

theme_set(theme_minimal(base_size = 13))

## **1) Question & audience**

::: callout-important

**Question.** How do **species** and **island** relate to **body mass** and **bill measurements** in penguins, and what patterns emerge across **sex**?

**Intended audience.** Public-health and ecology students learning tidy data analysis and visualization who want an approachable, fully reproducible example.

:::

::: {.column-margin}

**Margin note:** The Palmer Archipelago hosts Adelie, Gentoo, and Chinstrap penguinsâ€”classic for tidyverse teaching.

:::

**2) Data source & data dictionary**

-   **Original data:** The palmerpenguins R package provides cleaned measurements of penguins from the Palmer Archipelago, Antarctica \[\@horst2020palmerpenguins\].

-   **Where to get it:** CRAN package palmerpenguins.

-   **Data dictionary:** https://allisonhorst.github.io/palmerpenguins/reference/penguins.html

    peng \<- penguins \|\> janitor::clean_names() \|\> \# clean_names() tidyr::drop_na(species, island, sex, body_mass_g, bill_length_mm, bill_depth_mm) \|\> \# drop_na() dplyr::mutate( body_mass_kg = body_mass_g / 1000, \# mutate() species = forcats::fct_reorder(species, body_mass_kg, .fun = median) ) \|\> dplyr::select(species, island, sex, bill_length_mm, bill_depth_mm, body_mass_kg) \|\> \# select() dplyr::arrange(species, island) \# arrange()

    long_bills \<- peng \|\> tidyr::pivot_longer( \# pivot_longer() c(bill_length_mm, bill_depth_mm), names_to = "bill_metric", values_to = "bill_value" )
